Does your baby take a pacifier? Did he take it easily or did you have to work for it? What shape/brand works best for your baby?⁣
⁣
𝗦𝗼𝗺𝗲 𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗺𝗼𝗻 𝗾𝘂𝗲𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀 𝗜 𝗴𝗲𝘁 𝗮𝗯𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿𝘀: ⁣
⁣
𝗦𝗵𝗼𝘂𝗹𝗱 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆 𝘂𝘀𝗲 𝗮 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿?⁣
It’s up to you and your little one! 💕⁣
⁣
Here are reasons I love the pacifier:⁣
✅Releases endorphins⁣
✅Promotes relaxation⁣
✅Decreases the risk of SIDS⁣
✅ Soothes symptoms of reflux⁣
⁣
𝗜'𝗺 𝗮 𝗻𝘂𝗿𝘀𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗺𝗼𝗺, 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆 𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗹𝗹 𝗵𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝗮 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿? 𝗪𝗵𝗲𝗻?⁣
Absolutely! 💗 You will always want to respond to hunger cues with a feeding, but a pacifier IS acceptable, even for breastfed babies. Research shows that nursing moms who introduce a pacifier early are JUST as successful with nursing as those who wait. (𝘛𝘩𝘪𝘴 𝘳𝘦𝘴𝘦𝘢𝘳𝘤𝘩 𝘪𝘴 𝘭𝘪𝘯𝘬𝘦𝘥 𝘪𝘯 𝘴𝘵𝘰𝘳𝘪𝘦𝘴 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘮𝘺 "𝘐𝘯𝘵𝘳𝘰𝘥𝘶𝘤𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘢 𝘗𝘢𝘤𝘪𝘧𝘪𝘦𝘳" 𝘣𝘭𝘰𝘨.) ⁣
⁣
𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗶𝗳 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆 𝗴𝗮𝗴𝘀 𝗼𝗿 𝗽𝘂𝘀𝗵𝗲𝘀 𝗶𝘁 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝗵𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼𝗻𝗴𝘂𝗲? 𝗗𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝘀 𝗺𝗲𝗮𝗻 𝘀𝗵𝗲 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀𝗻’𝘁 𝘄𝗮𝗻𝘁 𝗶𝘁?⁣
These are actually reflexes, so probably not. See the tips in this video to help!⁣
⁣
𝗜𝗳 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀𝗻’𝘁 𝘁𝗮𝗸𝗲 𝗮 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿, 𝘀𝗵𝗼𝘂𝗹𝗱 𝗜 𝗸𝗲𝗲𝗽 𝗼𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗶𝘁? ⁣
For babies younger than 12 weeks, you can offer different shapes and brands a few times each day. Use the techniques shown in this video about 30 minutes after a feeding and when baby is calm. ⁣
*️⃣Most won’t accept it after 10-12 weeks if they haven’t accepted it prior. ⁣
⁣
𝗜𝘀 𝗮 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝗿𝗲𝗾𝘂𝗶𝗿𝗲𝗱 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗧𝗮𝗸𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗖𝗮𝗿𝗮 𝗕𝗮𝗯𝗶𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀? ⁣
Although pacifiers are a helpful tool in the newborn stage, they are NOT a requirement for any of my classes. You can have a great little sleeper with, or without, a pacifier. (𝘓𝘪𝘯𝘬 𝘵𝘰 𝘤𝘭𝘢𝘴𝘴𝘦𝘴 𝘪𝘯 𝘮𝘺 𝘣𝘪𝘰!) 😊⁣
⁣
What if the pacifier becomes an issue and makes our nights and naps more difficult?⁣
I have a blog for you with tips and videos to help. 😉 (𝘚𝘦𝘦 𝘭𝘪𝘯𝘬 𝘪𝘯 𝘣𝘪𝘰 𝘧𝘰𝘳 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘣𝘭𝘰𝘨 𝘰𝘳 𝘵𝘰𝘥𝘢𝘺’𝘴 𝘴𝘵𝘰𝘳𝘪𝘦𝘴!) ⁣

Sleep deprivation is HARD! ❤️ When I learned how to get my baby to sleep, I was finally able to be the mom I so desired to be for her. ⁣
⁣
How about YOU? How did solid sleep help you with your parenting journey? Would you share your story below? ⁣
⁣
*️⃣ To the mama out there struggling with sleep, here’s what I want you to know:⁣
⁣
If what you’re doing is working (and is safe), you don’t have to change anything. ⁣
HOWEVER, if you are struggling, help is available! You don’t have to walk this road alone. I have a class that can help you! ⁣
⁣
⁣Look at what this mama had to say: ⁣
“𝘐𝘵 𝘸𝘢𝘴 𝘧𝘪𝘷𝘦 𝘮𝘰𝘯𝘵𝘩𝘴 𝘰𝘧 𝘴𝘭𝘦𝘦𝘱 𝘥𝘦𝘱𝘳𝘪𝘷𝘢𝘵𝘪𝘰𝘯 𝘸𝘪𝘵𝘩 𝘰𝘶𝘳 𝘴𝘸𝘦𝘦𝘵 𝘣𝘢𝘣𝘺 𝘣𝘰𝘺. 𝘐 𝘸𝘰𝘶𝘭𝘥 𝘥𝘳𝘪𝘷𝘦 𝘪𝘯 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘥𝘢𝘺 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘧𝘦𝘦𝘭 𝘭𝘪𝘬𝘦 𝘐 𝘸𝘢𝘴 𝘥𝘳𝘶𝘯𝘬 𝘥𝘳𝘪𝘷𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘣𝘦𝘤𝘢𝘶𝘴𝘦 𝘐 𝘸𝘢𝘴 𝘴𝘰 𝘦𝘹𝘵𝘳𝘦𝘮𝘦𝘭𝘺 𝘵𝘪𝘳𝘦𝘥, 𝘦𝘷𝘦𝘳𝘺 𝘧𝘪𝘣𝘦𝘳 𝘰𝘧 𝘮𝘺 𝘣𝘦𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘸𝘢𝘴 𝘦𝘹𝘩𝘢𝘶𝘴𝘵𝘦𝘥. 𝘈𝘯𝘥 𝘸𝘦 𝘩𝘢𝘷𝘦 𝘢 𝘵𝘰𝘥𝘥𝘭𝘦𝘳 𝘴𝘰 𝘐 𝘩𝘢𝘥 𝘵𝘰 𝘣𝘦 “𝘰𝘯" 𝘧𝘰𝘳 𝘩𝘦𝘳 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘦𝘷𝘦𝘳𝘺 𝘱𝘢𝘳𝘵 𝘰𝘧 𝘮𝘦 𝘧𝘦𝘭𝘵 𝘴𝘰 𝘢𝘸𝘧𝘶𝘭 - 𝘱𝘩𝘺𝘴𝘪𝘤𝘢𝘭𝘭𝘺, 𝘮𝘦𝘯𝘵𝘢𝘭𝘭𝘺 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘦𝘮𝘰𝘵𝘪𝘰𝘯𝘢𝘭𝘭𝘺. 𝘐 𝘩𝘰𝘯𝘦𝘴𝘵𝘭𝘺 𝘧𝘦𝘭𝘵 𝘥𝘦𝘴𝘱𝘦𝘳𝘢𝘵𝘦 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘵𝘦𝘳𝘳𝘪𝘧𝘪𝘦𝘥 𝘵𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘐 𝘸𝘰𝘶𝘭𝘥 𝘯𝘦𝘷𝘦𝘳 𝘴𝘭𝘦𝘦𝘱 𝘢𝘨𝘢𝘪𝘯. 𝘕𝘰𝘵 𝘵𝘰 𝘮𝘦𝘯𝘵𝘪𝘰𝘯 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘴𝘵𝘳𝘢𝘪𝘯 𝘪𝘵 𝘸𝘢𝘴 𝘱𝘶𝘵𝘵𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘰𝘯 𝘰𝘶𝘳 𝘧𝘢𝘮𝘪𝘭𝘺. 𝘞𝘦 𝘵𝘰𝘰𝘬 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘛𝘢𝘬𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘊𝘢𝘳𝘢 𝘉𝘢𝘣𝘪𝘦𝘴 “𝘈𝘉𝘊’𝘴 𝘰𝘧 𝘚𝘭𝘦𝘦𝘱” 𝘤𝘰𝘶𝘳𝘴𝘦 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘪𝘵 𝘴𝘢𝘷𝘦𝘥 𝘶𝘴. 𝘚𝘭𝘦𝘦𝘱 𝘪𝘴 𝘢 𝘨𝘪𝘧𝘵 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘐 𝘤𝘢𝘯’𝘵 𝘵𝘩𝘢𝘯𝘬 𝘺𝘰𝘶 𝘦𝘯𝘰𝘶𝘨𝘩 𝘧𝘰𝘳 𝘱𝘳𝘰𝘷𝘪𝘥𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘪𝘵 𝘵𝘰 𝘶𝘴!”⁣
@natapicture⁣
⁣
➡️ “The ABC’s of Sleep” is my 14 night plan for 5-24 month olds. It will help your baby get 10-12 hour nights in the crib. I’ll walk you step-by-step through it and show you how to be emotionally present with your little one throughout the entire process. ⁣
⁣
Sleep deprivation doesn’t have to rule your world. ❤️ Be sure to see my stories today for more families’ experiences!

node.text:
Short naps can be so tough...They prevent baby from getting that restorative daytime sleep, make it difficult for parents to get any work done, and can lead to night struggles too. 😫⁣
 ⁣
Let’s break down some important info about short naps:⁣
➡A short nap is defined as less than one sleep cycle (or less than 40-50 minutes.)⁣
➡Naps have a developmental component. This means it’s NORMAL for naps to be unpredictable and short in the first four months.⁣
➡Around 5-months-old, naps BEGIN to regulate...But, mastering this skill can still take some practice!⁣
⁣
✨𝘚𝘦𝘦 𝘮𝘺 𝘩𝘪𝘨𝘩𝘭𝘪𝘨𝘩𝘵𝘦𝘥 𝘴𝘵𝘰𝘳𝘺 "𝘚𝘩𝘰𝘳𝘵 𝘕𝘢𝘱𝘴𝟸" 𝘧𝘰𝘳 𝘮𝘰𝘳𝘦 𝘵𝘪𝘱𝘴!✨⁣
⁣
If you've successfully broken the cycle of short naps: What helped the most? What words of encouragement do you have for parents going through this?⁣
⁣
If you are currently struggling with short naps: Use the tips in this reel, be sure to see the comments below, and know that you are not alone. There is hope! Those naps WILL lengthen! 💕

💨 Do you have a gassy baby on your hands?! 💨 ⁣
Gas is a NORMAL by-product of digestion, but gas can cause pain as it stretches the intestine, leaving your little one with an uncomfortable belly ache. ⁣Extra gas = extra FUSSINESS. 😫😫😫⁣
⁣
➡️If these tips aren’t working: Talk to your doctor about Mylicon drops and perhaps a change in diet or formula. (Lactose and Casein can be a big culprit for gassy babies.) ⁣
⁣
*️⃣Please know that often overtired little ones can mimic the signs of discomfort, too. 😳 The newborn class can teach you ways to calm your baby and prevent overtiredness. (Link in bio and stories!)⁣
⁣
Who has experience with a gassy baby? Can you encourage other parents? Anyone think their little one was in pain with gas or colic, but found the newborn class to be helpful in calming a fussy baby?⁣

Does your baby take a pacifier? Did he take it easily or did you have to work for it? What shape/brand works best for your baby?⁣
⁣
𝗦𝗼𝗺𝗲 𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗺𝗼𝗻 𝗾𝘂𝗲𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀 𝗜 𝗴𝗲𝘁 𝗮𝗯𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿𝘀: ⁣
⁣
𝗦𝗵𝗼𝘂𝗹𝗱 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆 𝘂𝘀𝗲 𝗮 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿?⁣
It’s up to you and your little one! 💕⁣
⁣
Here are reasons I love the pacifier:⁣
✅Releases endorphins⁣
✅Promotes relaxation⁣
✅Decreases the risk of SIDS⁣
✅ Soothes symptoms of reflux⁣
⁣
𝗜'𝗺 𝗮 𝗻𝘂𝗿𝘀𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗺𝗼𝗺, 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆 𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗹𝗹 𝗵𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝗮 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿? 𝗪𝗵𝗲𝗻?⁣
Absolutely! 💗 You will always want to respond to hunger cues with a feeding, but a pacifier IS acceptable, even for breastfed babies. Research shows that nursing moms who introduce a pacifier early are JUST as successful with nursing as those who wait. (𝘛𝘩𝘪𝘴 𝘳𝘦𝘴𝘦𝘢𝘳𝘤𝘩 𝘪𝘴 𝘭𝘪𝘯𝘬𝘦𝘥 𝘪𝘯 𝘴𝘵𝘰𝘳𝘪𝘦𝘴 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘮𝘺 "𝘐𝘯𝘵𝘳𝘰𝘥𝘶𝘤𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘢 𝘗𝘢𝘤𝘪𝘧𝘪𝘦𝘳" 𝘣𝘭𝘰𝘨.) ⁣
⁣
𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗶𝗳 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆 𝗴𝗮𝗴𝘀 𝗼𝗿 𝗽𝘂𝘀𝗵𝗲𝘀 𝗶𝘁 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝗵𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼𝗻𝗴𝘂𝗲? 𝗗𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝘀 𝗺𝗲𝗮𝗻 𝘀𝗵𝗲 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀𝗻’𝘁 𝘄𝗮𝗻𝘁 𝗶𝘁?⁣
These are actually reflexes, so probably not. See the tips in this video to help!⁣
⁣
𝗜𝗳 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀𝗻’𝘁 𝘁𝗮𝗸𝗲 𝗮 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿, 𝘀𝗵𝗼𝘂𝗹𝗱 𝗜 𝗸𝗲𝗲𝗽 𝗼𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗶𝘁? ⁣
For babies younger than 12 weeks, you can offer different shapes and brands a few times each day. Use the techniques shown in this video about 30 minutes after a feeding and when baby is calm. ⁣
*️⃣Most won’t accept it after 10-12 weeks if they haven’t accepted it prior. ⁣
⁣
𝗜𝘀 𝗮 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝗿𝗲𝗾𝘂𝗶𝗿𝗲𝗱 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗧𝗮𝗸𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗖𝗮𝗿𝗮 𝗕𝗮𝗯𝗶𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀? ⁣
Although pacifiers are a helpful tool in the newborn stage, they are NOT a requirement for any of my classes. You can have a great little sleeper with, or without, a pacifier. (𝘓𝘪𝘯𝘬 𝘵𝘰 𝘤𝘭𝘢𝘴𝘴𝘦𝘴 𝘪𝘯 𝘮𝘺 𝘣𝘪𝘰!) 😊⁣
⁣
What if the pacifier becomes an issue and makes our nights and naps more difficult?⁣
I have a blog for you with tips and videos to help. 😉 (𝘚𝘦𝘦 𝘭𝘪𝘯𝘬 𝘪𝘯 𝘣𝘪𝘰 𝘧𝘰𝘳 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘣𝘭𝘰𝘨 𝘰𝘳 𝘵𝘰𝘥𝘢𝘺’𝘴 𝘴𝘵𝘰𝘳𝘪𝘦𝘴!) ⁣

Sharing this reel again because it sparked such great conversation around the holidays last year! Sometimes we ALL need to set boundaries, yes, even with family members. 💕⁣
⁣
Please hear my heart. Your family means well. Their advice is almost always coming from a place of love and a desire to support you...⁣
⁣
BUT - here's the truth: ⁣
⭐ Nobody knows that baby like YOU do. No one is better equipped to make decisions and choices for that sweet little one than you! 💕⁣
⁣
So, research and learn all you can. ⁣
Then, trust yourself. ⁣
Make the choice that is right for your baby and your family and stick to it! ⁣
⁣
⭐️ 𝘞𝘢𝘭𝘬 𝘤𝘰𝘯𝘧𝘪𝘥𝘦𝘯𝘵𝘭𝘺 𝘪𝘯 𝘸𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘺𝘰𝘶 𝘬𝘯𝘰𝘸. ⭐️⁣
⁣
It’s okay to keep an open mind and truly learn from others, AND it’s equally okay to say, “Thank you so much for your advice, but this is what we've decided is best for us.” ⁣
⁣
Can I give you a tip? ⁣
 ⁣
🔹 When making parenting decisions that you know family members may not understand or agree with, practice your responses AHEAD of time. Know what you plan to say before the comments or questions start coming. 💕⁣
⁣
Be sure to see my stories for a printable Safe Sleep Checklist that can be a great conversation starter too!⁣
⁣
Have you had to set boundaries with family when it comes to your parenting choices? What has that looked like for you?

Daycare Parents, want to know a secret?🤫⁣
⁣
Some of the BEST little nappers I know are babies who attend daycare...it’s true!⁣
⁣
𝘓𝘦𝘵’𝘴 𝘵𝘢𝘭𝘬 𝘵𝘩𝘳𝘰𝘶𝘨𝘩 𝘵𝘰𝘥𝘢𝘺'𝘴 𝘳𝘦𝘦𝘭 𝘢 𝘣𝘪𝘵!⁣
➡If your baby sleeps best at home in a dark room, wearing a sleep sack, and has the sound of white noise humming in the background...that’s great! Keep doing it!⁣
➡Get naps at home in whatever way helps your baby to sleep. It doesn’t matter that daycare is brighter and uses music during nap time. You don’t have to try to replicate how they do it! Little ones really do understand the difference between home and daycare environments.⁣
➡️If daycare has your baby napping only once, but two naps work best at home, do two naps for a bit. ⁣
✨𝗣𝗿𝗼 𝗧𝗶𝗽: ask daycare if you can bring in a sound machine and sleep sack for your baby’s nap time. ⁣
⁣
𝘕𝘦𝘹𝘵, 𝘣𝘦 𝘴𝘶𝘳𝘦 𝘵𝘰 𝘢𝘥𝘫𝘶𝘴𝘵 𝘺𝘰𝘶𝘳 𝘣𝘢𝘣𝘺'𝘴 𝘣𝘦𝘥𝘵𝘪𝘮𝘦 𝘢𝘴 𝘯𝘦𝘦𝘥𝘦𝘥.⁣
➡Remember, we always want a full wake window prior to bedtime (see stories for more on this!), but bedtime can be as early as 6pm if needed.⁣
➡An early bedtime really can help relieve some of that sleep debt that your baby is experiencing during the day. Night sleep IS the most restorative. ⁣
⁣
Finally, know that daycare is an adjustment and will take time. Be patient and know that sleep progress will come. 💕⁣
⁣
𝗛𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝗺𝗼𝗿𝗲 𝗱𝗮𝘆𝗰𝗮𝗿𝗲 𝗾𝘂𝗲𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀? Check out my “Daycare and Baby Sleep” blog! (Link in bio and stories.) ⁣
⁣
Has anyone recently started daycare? How did the transition go? Do you have any tips for parents with kiddos starting daycare soon?
